translated_by_TA:
Chopin: an inventory
nearly sixty mazurkas; about thirty studies;
two dozen preludes; about twenty nocturnes;
about fifteen waltzes; more than a dozen “polonaises”;
“scherzos”, improvisations, and ballads, four of each;
three piano sonatas; and two concertos for piano and orchestra,
a “berceuse”, a barcarolle, a fantasy, a tarantella, etc.,
in addition to some seventeen songs for voice and piano; a fatal tuberculosis;
a talent as a concert pianist; many worldly successes; an unhappy passion;
a famous affair with an illustrious woman; other assorted liaisons;
a homeland without secure borders or concrete independence;
the French Europe of romanticism; several friendships with eminent men;
and only thirty-nine years of life. Others lived less, wrote more, ate the classically bitter bread of exile more bitterly, were ignored or fought against, died abandoned, did not stroll in the bedrooms or halls of glory, confined themselves less to the instrument they mastered best, and were even more stateless, suffering from a homeland that does not exist. In addition, almost all of them escaped more the repellent possibility of being the melody of virgins, the rhythm of castrated people, the half-bowl swing, the nostalgia of illiterates, and other mediocre and petty things of vulgarity, as he did not. Or of being a dish of non-resistance for concert performers who play for people who think they like music but do not. On top of that, he was an upstart, a pedant convinced of the aristocracy he did not have, a reactionary yearning for revolutions that would free the oligarchies of Poland, poor things, and others. and, to top it all off,
we begin to suspect that he wasn't even a romantic,
at least in the way he pretended to be and let it be understood that he was.
an art of composing music as if writing a poem,
the strength that disguises itself in languor, an air of inspiration
concealing the structure, a harmonic melancholy over
the melodic irony (or the opposite), the magic of rhythms
used to hide thought - and hide it so much,
that this man who had his thoughts in his fingers,
and whose audacity used the mask of feeling or free forms
to create himself, still seems like a fool of a genius. So skilled in his cuisine, that he can serve himself
lukewarm, in times of longing and bitterness,
hot, on the great occasions of triumphant life,
and cold, when only music will express the empty despair
of being a piano and nothing else in the world.
